{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "When someone has been wrongfully convicted and imprisoned, a cash payout is the most meaningful way to achieve some measure of belated justice.", "abstract": "Editorial welcomes announcement by New York City Comptroller Scott Stringer that city will remit total of $17 million to Robert Hill, Alvena Jennette and Darryl Austin, who were wrongly convicted of murders due to corrupt tactics of homicide detective Louis Scarcella; concedes that payout is less than men may have gotten through civil lawsuit, but that at least it is immediate and certain; calls on every state to set up some sort of monetary compensation for those who have been wrongly convicted and imprisoned.", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "24", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [], "organization": "THE EDITORIAL BOARD", "original": "By THE EDITORIAL BOARD", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/14/opinion/the-dollar-value-of-a-stolen-life.html", "lead_paragraph": "When someone has been wrongfully convicted and imprisoned, a cash payout is the most meaningful way to achieve some measure of belated justice.", "headline": {"print_headline": "The Dollar Value of a Stolen Life", "main": "The Dollar Value of a Stolen Life", "content_kicker": "Editorial", "kicker": "Editorial"}, "_id": "54b62fa638f0d82829edf1f6", "word_count": "521", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 397, "url": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "397"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-thumbStanda